<statement>
<p>
Determine whether the following four statements are true or false. Explain your answers.
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
<p>
 <m>\forall y\in  \mathbb{R}, \forall z\in \mathbb{R}, \exists x\in
\mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. }  x+y=z</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>\exists x\in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } \forall y\in  \mathbb{R}, \forall z\in
\mathbb{R}, x+y=z</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>\forall x\in \mathbb{R}, \exists y \in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } \exists z \in
\mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } \text{if }z \gt y \text{ then } z \gt x+y</m>.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 <m>\forall x\in \mathbb{R}, \exists y \in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } \forall z \in
\mathbb{R}, \text{ if }z \gt y \text{ then } z \gt x+y</m>.
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<hint>
<p>
Be careful of the order of quantifiers; make sure you pick variables in the correct order.
</p>
</hint>
<solution>
<p>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
<p>
 True. Let <m>y,z</m> be any real numbers, and then pick <m>x=z-y</m> (which is a real). Then <m>x+y = z-y+y = z</m> as required.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 False. The negation of the statement is  <m>\forall x\in \mathbb{R}, \exists y \in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } \exists z \in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } x+y \neq z</m>. So let <m>x</m> be any real number and then set <m>y=-x</m> and <m>z=1</m>. Then <m>x+y = x-y = 0 \neq 1 = z</m>. Since the negation is true, the original is false.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 True. Recall that when the hypothesis is false the implication is true. So let <m>x</m> be any real number and set <m>y=1, z=0</m>. Then <m>z = 0 \lt 1 =y</m>, so the hypothesis is false, making the implication true.
</p></li>
<li>
<p>
 False. The negation is <m>\exists x \in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } \forall y \in \mathbb{R}, \exists z \in \mathbb{R} \text{ s.t. } (z \gt y) \land (z \leq x+y)</m>. So pick <m>x=2</m> and then let <m>y</m> be any real number. Now set <m>z=y+1</m>, then <m>z =y+1 \gt y</m> and <m>z = y+1 \leq y+2 = x+y</m>. Since the negation is true, the original is false.
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
